{{Infobox language |name=Chiquitano |nativename=''Besïro'' |states=[[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz]], [[Bolivia]] |ethnicity=47,100 [[Chiquitano people]] (2004)<ref name=e18/> |speakers={{sigfig|5860|2}} in Bolivia |date=2004 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |family=[[Language isolate]] |iso3=cax |glotto=chiq1248 |glottoname=Chiquitano |glotto2=sans1265 |glottoname2=Sansimoniano |notice=IPA }}
'''Chiquitano''' (also ''Bésiro'' or ''Tarapecosi'') is an indigenous [[language isolate]] of eastern [[Bolivia]], spoken in the central region of the [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz]] province.
==Classification== Chiquitano is a [[language isolate]]. Greenberg linked it to the [[Macro-Jê languages]] in his discredited proposal, which was never substantiated.
According to traditional sources, dialects were ''tao (yúnkarirsh), piñoco, penoqui, kusikia, manasi, san simoniano, churapa.''
