{{Infobox language |name=Chomo |nativename=Chomowa, D˚romowa |altname=Tromo, Chumbi |states=[[China]], [[Bhutan]] and [[India]] |region=Chumbi Valley region between [[Sikkim]] and [[Bhutan]] |speakers=27,000 |date=1993–2007 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=[[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] ? |fam3=[[Bodish languages|Bodish]] |fam4=[[Tibetic languages|Tibetic]] |fam5=Dzongkha–Lhokä |iso3=gro |glotto=grom1238 |glottorefname=Groma }}
'''Chomo''' ([[Tibetan pinyin|ZYPY]]), also '''Chumbi''' or '''D˚romo''' ([[Roman Dzongkha]]), is a language spoken in [[Yadong COunty|Chomo (Yadong) County]], Tibet, China. It is also spoken in [[Sikkim]], India. It belongs to the southern group of Tibetan languages. Its speakers identify as [[Tibetan people|Tibetans]].
