[[Image:Gysbert Japix portrait by Matthijs Harings.tif|thumb|250px|Gysbert Japicx, 1637, portrait by Matthijs Harings]] '''Gysbert Japiks''' or '''Japicx''' or '''Japix''' (1603&ndash;1666) was a [[West Frisians|West Frisian]] writer, poet, [[schoolmaster]], and [[Cantus|cantor]].
==Life== Japiks was born in [[Bolsward]], Friesland. He admired the [[Latin]] poets [[Horace]] and [[Ovid]], but was also an enthusiast for his own [[Middle Frisian language|West Frisian]] ''memmetaal'', or [[mother tongue]]. His work was the most notable in that language of his day and had the effect of elevating Frisian to literary status.<ref>Roderick Jellema, ''Country fair: poems from Friesland since 1945 in Frisian and English'' (Eerdmans, 1985), pp. xiv–xv</ref> The poems of Japiks were published in ''Friessche Tjerne'' (1640) and also posthumously in ''Fryske Rijmlerye'' (1668).<ref>Horst Haider Munske, Nils Århammar, Volker F. Faltings, ''Handbuch des Friesischen / Handbook of Frisian Studies'' (2001), p. 710</ref>
==Songs== Japiks's Frisian songs were [[contrafacta]] to well-known tunes by composers such as [[Goudimel]], [[Louis Bourgeois (composer)|Bourgeois]], and [[Pierre Guédron]]. A selection from them was recorded by Frisian singers and [[Camerata Trajectina]] in 2003.<ref>''Gysbert Japix (1603-1666)'', Frisian soloists: Tetsje van der Kooi, soprano; Femke de Boer, alto; Jaap Hoekstra, tenor; Siebren Kramer, baritone; Rozemarijn Palma, song; GLO 6055</ref>
