{{Infobox language |name=Olrat |states=[[Vanuatu]] |region=[[Gaua]] |speakers=3 |date=2012 |ref=<ref name="sociolg"/> |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Southern Oceanic languages|Southern Oceanic]] |fam5=Vanuatu |fam6=[[Northern Vanuatu languages|Northern Vanuatu]] |fam7=[[East Vanuatu languages|East Vanuatu]] |iso3=olr |glotto=none }} {{distinguish|OLRAT}}
'''Olrat''' is a moribund [[Oceanic language]] spoken on [[Gaua|Gaua island]] in [[Vanuatu]].
==The language== [[File:Alex-Maten-Gaua-2003.jpg|thumb|left|250px|upright|<center>A. François with †Maten Womal, the last storyteller of Olrat <small>([[Gaua]], [[Vanuatu]], 2003)</small></center>]] The three remaining speakers of Olrat live on the middle-west coast of Gaua.<ref>[http://alex.francois.free.fr/AF-field.htm List of Banks islands languages].</ref> They merged into the larger village of Jōlap where [[Lakon language|Lakon]] is dominant, after they left their inland hamlet of Olrat in the first half of the 20th century.<ref name="sociolg">{{Harvcoltxt|François|2012}}.</ref>
[[Alexandre François (linguist)|Alexandre François]] identifies Olrat as a distinct language from its immediate neighbor [[Lakon language|Lakon]], on phonological,<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2005}}</ref> grammatical,<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2007}}</ref> and lexical<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2011}}</ref> grounds. {{-}} ==Phonology== Olrat has 14 [[phoneme|phonemic]] vowels. These include 7 short /i ɪ ɛ a ɔ ʊ u/ and 7 long vowels /iː ɪː ɛː aː ɔː ʊː uː/.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2005|p=445}}, {{Harvcoltxt|François|2011|p=194}}.</ref>
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;" |+ Olrat vowels |- ! &nbsp; !! [[Front vowel|Front]] !! [[Back vowel|Back]] |- ! [[near-close vowel|Near-close]] | {{IPA link|i}} ∙ {{IPA link|iː}} || {{IPA link|u}} ∙ {{IPA link|uː}} |- ! [[close-mid vowel|Close-mid]] | {{IPA link|ɪ}} ∙ {{IPA link|ɪː}} || {{IPA link|ʊ}} ∙ {{IPA link|ʊː}} |- ! [[open-mid vowel|Open-mid]] | {{IPA link|ɛ}} ∙ {{IPA link|ɛː}} || {{IPA link|ɔ}} ∙ {{IPA link|ɔː}} |- ! [[open vowel|Open]] | colspan="2" | {{IPA link|a}} ∙ {{IPA link|aː}} |}
Historically, the phonologization of vowel length originates in the [[compensatory lengthening]] of short vowels when the [[voiced velar fricative]] {{IPA|/ɣ/}} was lost syllable-finally.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|François|2005|p=461}}.</ref>
